Domain 5 Review:

domain 5, secure software implementation, highlights the concepts and methodologies that allow all stakeholders involved in the software development life cycle (SDLC), from operations personnel to architects, to execute best application security practices and deliver secure software










Functional vs. Nonfunctional Security Testing:

functional involves testing what security has to do; describes a function (behavior) that enforces security. can be directly testing and observed. example, stop unauthorized access attempts

nonfunctional security testing involves testing what security has to be; describes a function that supports a security process. example, audit logs created from access control will be verbose enough to support forensics. supporting auditability is not a direct functional requirement for access control

derived requirements are inspired by functional and nonfunctional requirements. example, an access control system uses two-factor authentication; a derived requirement would be the number of allowable incorrect tries before a user is locked out of the system. for the audit log, a derived requirement might support log integrity (log injection protection)











Security Testing:

white-box, privileged insider

black-box, outsider perspective

gray-box, normal insider, guest, external user, internet facing











Testing Methodology:

create a test strategy; create a test plan, gather necessary tools, implement the plan, document the results, fix the problems











Testing Techniques:

alpha testing; normally conducted by insiders. completed before limited release

beta testing; limited release, performed by "real" users

pilot testing; AKA field testing or market testing. small scale preliminary test conducted to evaluate feasibility, duration, cost and adverse events and improve upon the design prior to performance of a full-scale implementation

regression testing; testing after changes. confirm changes did not break functionality or security













