Attack Surface Validation:

identify the parts of software that need to be reviewed for vulnerabilities

testing to see if the software can be broken

motive, opportunity and means













Attack Surface Analyzer:

Microsoft built open source tool

enables development team to view changes in the windows attack surface resulting from the installation of the application, assess the aggregate attack surface change associated with the application in the enterprise environment, evaluate the risk to the platform where the application is proposed to exist, and provide incident response teams detailed information associated with a windows platform

operates independently from the application under review










Simulation Testing:

when software that functions without any problems in the development environment experiences hiccups in the production environments, it is indicative of issues with configuration management

this means that the development and production environments are disparate in their configurations

since it is not advisable to conduct software testing in the production environment, a mirrored or simulated environment needs to be created. the software should be tested in this simulated environment

because the configuration settings of the production (operational) environment are simulated, any issues of the software not working can be determined early and addressed prior to deployment

the simulated environment may used synthetic data and transaction rather than actual production data













Cryptographic Validation:

standards conformance; especially FIPS 140-2 requirements

environment validation

data validation

cryptographic implementation tests

use pseudo-random number generators and entropy











FIPS 140-2:

the prescribed standard, part of the federal information processing standards series that relates to the implementation of cryptographic functions

deals with issues such as the selection of approved algorithms; AES, RSA, and DSA

deals with the environment where the cryptographic functions are used

deals with ways of implementation











Regression Tests:

business requirements change over time and new functionality is added whenever code is modified, there is the potential for breaking existing functionality

regression tests; performed to determine if the software still meets all its requirements and modifications

involves repeating existing validation tests, not developing new tests

primarily focused on implementation issues over design flaws

performed before software is release to ensure that the software does not regress to a non functional or insecure state

sometime referred to as verification tests











Unit Testing and Code Coverage:

tests the smallest parts of an application (functions, procedure) to ensure they are fit for use

done during coding by developers

typically automated

often focused on code coverage; code coverage is how much of your code has been tested. in most cases, more is better and increases the trust in the code. it may be impossible to get 100% coverage and in many cases 80% is considered good coverage. calculated by lines of code tested/number of lines of code











Integration Tests:

the security of the sum of all parts should be tested

when an individual units of code are integrated and tested, it is referred to as integration testing

next logical testing step after unit testing














Continuous Testing:

process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline in order to obtain feedback on the business risks associated with a software release candidate as rapidly as possible

test artifacts can then be used to determine if the software is ready to progress through the delivery pipeline at any given time

can be used for both functional and security functional testing as well as other non functional testing

automation is key to continuous testing. however, automated testing is not the same as continuous testing














