Incident Management:

incident management activities are about the proper protocols to follow and the steps to take when a security breach (or incident) occurs

it is no longer about if it will happen; in todays world it is about when it will happen

three supporting areas of focus; root cause analysis, finding and fixing the real problem. incident triage, prioritizing a treatment strategy. forensics, discovering evidence. remediation, correcting problems










SP 800-61 rev.2:

computer security incident handling guide;

provides practical guidance on responding to incidents effectively and efficiently

system agnostic guidance

focuses on four parts of incident response; detecting, analyzing, prioritizing, and handling














Patch Management:

patches are additional pieces of code developed to address problems (commonly called "bugs") in software

patches enable additional functionality or address security flaws within a program. not all vulnerabilities have related patched; this, system administrators must not only be aware of applicable vulnerabilities and available patches, but also other methods of remediation (e.g. device or network configuration changes, employee training) that limit the exposure of systems to vulnerabilities

patches should be carefully testing before release

patches should be secured and released when ready for production












NIST SP 800-40 rev.4:

creating a patch and vulnerability management plan; provides guidelines on creating and running a patch management program. timely patching of security issues is generally recognized as critical. recommenfs a patch and vulnerability group (PVG)











Vulnerability Management:

